\u003Eteres major\u003C/strong\u003E muscle. It runs alongside the axillary artery and is an important structure in the axillary region, particularly in procedures involving central venous access.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eteres minor\u003C/strong\u003E is a muscle of the rotator cuff and is not related to the formation of the axillary vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epectoralis minor\u003C/strong\u003E is located anteriorly in the chest and does not mark the beginning of the axillary vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubscapularis\u003C/strong\u003E is another muscle of the rotator cuff and is not involved in the formation of the axillary vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erhomboid minor\u003C/strong\u003E is a muscle of the upper back and is not related to the axillary vein.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The axillary vein begins at the lower border of the teres major muscle.","Understanding the anatomy of the axillary vein is crucial for procedures involving central venous access."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{